  "candidate_learnings": "- Valproate syrup is stocked in >90 % of district‑level pharmacies in Uganda, is inexpensive (~$0.08 per dose), and is the preferred first‑line agent for early‑onset focal and generalized epilepsies per the Ugandan National Essential Medicines List and ILAE 2022 guidelines.\n- Carbamazepine, lamotrigine, and phenytoin are classified as aromatic AEDs; patients with a history of drug‑induced skin rash are advised to avoid these agents.\n- Levetiracetam is non‑aromatic and has a low rash risk, but its dispersible tablets are intermittently available and cost ~2–3 times more per mg than valproate, making it a secondary option when valproate is contraindicated or unavailable.\n- Phenobarbital tablets are widely available but are associated with a high sedation rate (~30 % of children) and are less favored for children with cerebral palsy or developmental delay; it is reserved for refractory cases after failure of two optimized first‑line AEDs.\n- In children weighing 8–12 kg, the recommended valproate starting dose is 10 mg/kg/day divided BID, titrated by 5–10 mg/kg every 1–2 weeks to a target of 20–30 mg/kg/day, with baseline and 1‑month LFT/CBC monitoring; this dosing schema yields seizure‑free rates >70 % in local cohorts.\n- adherence scores based on caregiver report and pharmacy refill data strongly predict seizure control; when adherence is low, the preferred strategy is to simplify regimens (single‑daily or twice‑daily dosing) rather than add additional agents.\n- Children with cerebral palsy and spastic tone benefit from AEDs with minimal sedation; valproate and levetiracetam are preferred over phenobarbital in this subgroup.\n- For infants with seizure onset <3 months and electrographic patterns of epileptic encephalopathy, early initiation of valproate (within the first month) is associated with improved developmental outcomes compared with delayed treatment.\n- Drug‑interaction profiles are critical: baclofen co‑administration does not significantly affect carbamazepine levels, whereas phenobarbital induces CYP enzymes and may reduce efficacy of concurrent antimalarials; valproate inhibition of CYP can increase plasma levels of co‑prescribed antiretrovirals.\n- Cost‑effectiveness analyses in Ugandan public health settings show that maintaining a child on valproate monotherapy (including monitoring) reduces total care costs by ~15 % relative to switching to phenobarbital or adding a second AED.",
